---
import Root from "../layouts/minimal.astro";
---

<Root title="I need a CMS">
  <div
    class="rounded-t-2xl bg-white/5 border-[0.5px] border-white/13 border-b-0 backdrop-blur-xl"
  >
    <div class="px-7 py-5 border-b border-white/7">
      <div class="yap">

      <h1>Heading one</h1>
      <h2>Heading two</h2>
      <h3>Heading three</h3>
      <h4>Heading four</h4>

      <p>This is a paragraph with <strong>bold text</strong>, <em>italic text</em>, and <strong><em>bold italic</em></strong>. It also has an <a href="#">inline link</a> and some <code>inline code</code> for good measure.</p>

      <p>A second paragraph to check spacing between paragraphs. Bytes don't arrive in neat packets. They arrive in whatever shape the kernel feels like — sometimes a full message, sometimes half.</p>

      <blockquote>
        <p>This is a blockquote. It should be visually distinct from the surrounding prose without being too loud.</p>
      </blockquote>

      <h2>h2 Lists</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>Unordered item one</li>
        <li>Unordered item two</li>
        <li>Unordered item three with a bit more text to see how wrapping behaves</li>
      </ul>

      <ol>
        <li>Ordered item one</li>
        <li>Ordered item two</li>
        <li>Ordered item three</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>h2 Code</h2>

      <p>Inline code looks like <code>this.value = 42</code> and sits in the flow of text.</p>

      <pre><code>fn main() {"{"}
          let x: u32 = 42;
          println!("hello, {}", x);
      }</code></pre>

      <hr>

      <h2>After a divider</h2>

      <p>Content after a horizontal rule. The rule should feel like a section break, not a decoration.</p>

      <figure>
        <img src="https://placehold.co/600x300" alt="A placeholder image" />
        <figcaption>This is a figure caption — small, muted, below the image.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Root>
